docs.abstract: Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told senators that the United States would soon fund Palestinian schools and promised sanctions against Venezuela.
docs.snippet: Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told senators that the United States would soon fund Palestinian schools and promised sanctions against Venezuela.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Secretary of State Mike Pompeo promised on Wednesday to impose additional sanctions on Venezuela, predicted that the United States would again fund schools for Palestinian refugees in Jordan and said that President Trump viewed Russia’s return to the Group of 7 as inevitable.

headline.main: Pompeo Outlines Plans for Global Challenges, Including Venezuela and Palestinian Refugees

docs.abstract: The group’s top lobbyist said the president and vice president “support the Second Amendment, support strong due process and don’t want gun control.”
docs.snippet: The group’s top lobbyist said the president and vice president “support the Second Amendment, support strong due process and don’t want gun control.”
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The top lobbyist for the National Rifle Association claimed late Thursday that President Trump had retreated from his surprising support a day earlier for gun control measures after a meeting with N.R.A. officials and Vice President Mike Pence in the Oval Office.

headline.main: N.R.A. Suggests Trump May Retreat From Gun Control
headline.print_headline: N.R.A. Says Trump May Retreat on Gun Control

docs.abstract: The lawyers believe the special counsel lacks standing in some matters, but a refusal would run counter to the president’s statements and raise the specter of a court battle.
docs.snippet: The lawyers believe the special counsel lacks standing in some matters, but a refusal would run counter to the president’s statements and raise the specter of a court battle.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Lawyers for President Trump have advised him against sitting down for a wide-ranging interview with the special counsel, Robert S. Mueller III, according to four people briefed on the matter, raising the specter of a monthslong court battle over whether the president must answer questions under oath.

headline.main: In Russia Inquiry, Lawyers Tell Trump to Refuse Mueller Interview
headline.print_headline: Lawyers Tell Trump to Refuse Mueller Interview

docs.abstract: Its handling of Rob Porter’s resignation has become a case study in how shifting stories can make matters worse.
docs.snippet: Its handling of Rob Porter’s resignation has become a case study in how shifting stories can make matters worse.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — By the time the furor over a presidential aide accused of spousal abuse reached a second week, the White House account of what happened became less clear, not more. The contradictions were multiplying. The daily news briefing was filled with caveats.

headline.main: The White House Flouts the First Rule of Crisis Communications: Get the Facts Out Fast
headline.print_headline: When Crisis Communications Becomes a Crisis All on Its Own

docs.abstract: The judge described himself as shaken by his experience in the case and portrayed a detainee’s former defense lawyers as pursuing a “revolution to the system” by defying judicial orders.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A deeply frustrated military judge on Friday halted the effort to use a military tribunal to prosecute a Guantánamo Bay detainee accused of orchestrating the 2000 bombing of the American destroyer Cole, bringing the already troubled case to an indefinite standstill.

headline.main: Frustrated Military Tribunal Judge Indefinitely Halts Cole Bombing Case

docs.abstract: The president unleashed a two-day Twitter tirade that was unusually angry and defiant even by his standards.
docs.snippet: The president unleashed a two-day Twitter tirade that was unusually angry and defiant even by his standards.
docs.lead_paragraph: WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. — President Trump began the weekend believing that something good had just happened to him. An indictment leveled against 13 Russians for interfering with the 2016 election had not accused him or anyone around him of wrongdoing. “No collusion” was his refrain.

headline.main: Trump’s Evolution From Relief to Fury Over the Russia Indictment
headline.print_headline: Trump’s Delight Over  Indictment Hardens to Fury

docs.snippet: In an extraordinary confrontation, the bipartisan leaders of the Senate Intelligence Committee told the House speaker that his troops had leaked a senator’s texts with a Russia-connected lawyer.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Senate Intelligence Committee has concluded that Republicans on the House Intelligence Committee were behind the leak of private text messages between the Senate panel’s top Democrat and a Russian-connected lawyer, according to two congressional officials briefed on the matter.

docs.abstract: A call between President Enrique Peña Nieto and President Trump descended into a quarrel over the wall, a topic that is fraying relations and blocking progress on vital issues.
docs.snippet: A call between President Enrique Peña Nieto and President Trump descended into a quarrel over the wall, a topic that is fraying relations and blocking progress on vital issues.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump’s refusal to publicly drop his demand that Mexico pay for a wall on its border with the United States has derailed tentative plans for President Enrique Peña Nieto to make his first visit to the Trump White House next month, after a contentious telephone call last week reinflamed tensions on the issue, American and Mexican officials said.

headline.main: Sharp Words Over Wall Halt Plans for Mexican President to Visit White House
headline.print_headline: Feud Over Wall Derails  Mexican Leader’s Visit

docs.abstract: Mr. Carson’s wife is accused of pressuring officials at the Department of Housing and Urban Development for an expensive redecoration of his office.
docs.snippet: Mr. Carson’s wife is accused of pressuring officials at the Department of Housing and Urban Development for an expensive redecoration of his office.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Department of Housing and Urban Development officials spent $31,000 on a new dining room set for Secretary Ben Carson’s office in late 2017 — just as the White House circulated its plans to slash HUD’s programs for the homeless, elderly and poor, according to federal procurement records.

headline.main: Ben Carson’s HUD Spends $31,000 on Dining Set for His Office
headline.print_headline: Budget Cuts at HUD, Except for Secretary’s Office
